==English==

===Verb===
{{en-verb|*}}

# To [[physically]] [[assemble]] (or [[reassemble]]) from [[fragment]]s or [[piece]]s.
#: {{ux|en|The community '''pieced together''' a quilt using a square stitched in each household.}}
#: {{ux|en|It took years for the archeologist to '''piece together''' the fragments of the shattered vase.}}
#* '''2013''', Tom Shone, "[http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/filmblog/2013/jan/11/oscar-nominations-surprise-taste Oscar nominations pull a surprise by showing some taste – but will it last?]", ''The Guardian'', 11 January 2013:
#*: Perhaps the best news to come out of the nominations was the brightened box-office prospects for such films as Benh Zeitlin's Beasts of the Southern Wild, a dazzling piece of magic realism '''pieced together''' from just $1.8m, some rusty bathtubs and whatever Louisiana bric-a-brac its youthful collective of film-makers could lay their hands on.
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} To [[reconstruct]] an event or goal from [[incomplete]] or [[flawed]] elements.
#: {{ux|en|The detective painstakingly collected clues to '''piece together''' what happened that tragic night.}}
#* '''2011''', Phil McNulty, "[http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15413593 Chelsea 3 - 5 Arsenal]", ''BBC Sport'', 29 October 2011:
#*: Arsenal have been '''piecing''' their season back '''together''' after a poor start and the manner of this win will provide added reserves of confidence and self-belief.

